## Sensitive terms

These terms have a higher potential to cause harm to individuals, communities, and Eightfold as a brand. To minimize risk, adhere to the following guidance:

### Race and ethnicity

Only refer to race and ethnicity when it is legally necessary or refers directly to a user control.

* Be as specific as possible  
* If necessary, use specific categories defined by the government. In the US, this would be the definitions provided by the EEOC and NIH.  
* Government definitions may not apply globally.   
* Always get legal review and feedback  
* Do not use POC (person of color)

### Workforce categories

Do not use: 

* Human capital

Use with caution:

* Blue collar  
* Skilled and unskilled labor

### Additional references

* [Conscious Style Guide](https://consciousstyleguide.com/)

#### **Anonymous, Anonymize ‚õîÔ∏è**

**Legal review required** 

* Under privacy laws, to ‚Äúanonymize‚Äù means to eliminate all personal data such that the person can no longer be re-identified

Guidance

* Be specific and descriptive about what the backend is actually doing with the data  
  * Try: mask, won‚Äôt show, hide, remove identifying information   
    * These are options to try, but **not** pre-approved   
    * Legal approval required

#### **Autosave, Autosaved, Autosaving** {#autosave,-autosaved,-autosaving}

Content patterns

| Use | Usage | Do not use |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Autosaved | Use in simpler forms or when space is small | Auto-save Auto save |
| All changes autosaved | Use only when precise time or date is not necessary Show only when changes have just autosaved Do not show when there are unsaved changes | All changes auto-saved All changes are autosaved |
| Autosaving all changes‚Ä¶ | Use when saving is in progress (not complete yet) Include ellipsis (three dots at end of text) to show action is still in progress | Auto-saving all changes Autosaving your changes  Autosaving your changes (missing ellipsis) |
| Autosaved {time} Examples: Autosaved 3:25 PM | Assumes date is clear from context and does not need to be messaged | Autosaved at {time} |
| Autosaved {time} {date} Examples![][image9]  | Both date formats shown in examples meet EF standards | Autosaved at {time} on {date} |
| Autosaved {time elapsed} Example: ![][image10] | Follow [standards for time elapsed](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1iH3BWI1ocmjB269ahoelXilebuvJGX4BkuDutba8plE/edit#bookmark=id.rsbmgblmyiyi) |  |

Guidance

* One word, no hyphen  
* No filler words (‚Äúat‚Äù, ‚Äúon‚Äù)  
* Be specific: do not state that ‚Äúall changes‚Äù are saved   
  * Reason: there is a window between user changes and system save when this statement is inaccurate  
  * Instead: specify time and date  
* Use processing text or icon when action is not yet complete  
  * See: ‚ÄúAutosaving‚Äù in content patterns

Related terms

#### **Confirm** {#confirm}

Definition

* Approve a choice or an action

Guidance

* Generally used for critical actions such as deletion, modification, and more  
* Ensure there is clarity in the action that is being confirmed. For example:  
  * Use ‚ÄòConfirm file upload‚Äô that asks for confirmation and mentions a specific action, instead of ‚ÄòUpload‚Äô  
  * Use ‚ÄòConfirm change password‚Äô in a confirmation window when a user initiates password change  
* Avoid confirming every action  
  * Excessive use reduces its importance and users might skip necessary confirmations

Related

* [Save](#save)  
* [Submit](#submit)

#### **Disable ‚ö†Ô∏è** {#disable-‚ö†Ô∏è}

| Use | Usage | Do not use |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Disable | Can be used as a CTA  [Standards for CTA](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1iH3BWI1ocmjB269ahoelXilebuvJGX4BkuDutba8plE/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.6ddt6uxu6ken) | Deactivate |
| Disable {feature name}  | When clarity is needed, add specific feature name. Use sentence case. |  |

Definition

* To make a feature or functionality unavailable for use

Guidance

* Use "Disable" to describe the action a user takes to turn off a specific feature or setting  
  * Consider simpler, less risky CTAs like: Turn off, Off (for a toggle design)  
* UI context must clearly indicate what is being disabled  
  * If context does not clarify, text must clarify  
* Clarify the consequences   
  * Users must understand what will happen and what they will no longer be able to do. Prevent bad surprises.  
  * Specify if data will be retained, deleted, or hidden

Risk prevention

* Consider privacy implications when a user disables a feature. If disabling affects the visibility or processing of personal information, get legal review.  
* The word ‚Äúdisable‚Äù is sensitive because it can also refer to physical or mental impairment  
  * Avoid using emotional language or assumptions. Be factual and focus on the functional impact.  
  * Review all text with this term and question if it can be misinterpreted as insensitive

**Related terms**

* [Enable](#enable)

#### **Draft** {#draft}

Definition

* A version of content (such as an email, message, or document) that is in progress and not yet finalized or sent.

Guidance

* Use "Draft" to indicate content that is being created or edited but has not been published, sent, or submitted  
* Clearly differentiate between a saved draft and sent/finalized content  
* Use with other terms like "Save" or "Edit" when more clarity is needed

| Use | Usage | Do not use |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Draft | Tag Example: ![][image24] | Saved Saved draft |
| Publish | Do not use in CTAs that change content status Does not add value \- context makes it clear what will be published Cognitive load \- technically a draft shows the content that will be published, but is not the thing that is actually published‚Ä¶ this is **not** what you want users slowing down to think about | Publish draft |
| Save draft Edit draft | [CTA standards](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1iH3BWI1ocmjB269ahoelXilebuvJGX4BkuDutba8plE/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.6ddt6uxu6ken) | Save Draft Edit Draft |
| Write email Create email | Do not use as a verb The option to save as a draft comes later in user flow Therefore, other verbs like ‚ÄúWrite‚Äù or ‚ÄúCreate‚Äù are more clear about the immediate next action | Draft email |
| 1 draft \<number\> drafts | Meta text Show when number of drafts is useful info Example: 3 drafts | 3 Drafts |

#### **Flagged activity**

Part of the [content system for AI Interviewer](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1L464whh7MbpeF7HQOU76GCeivy4JW1Ekf_BYRny-L30/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.dn6tavsp5wzr)

This term is used to mean 2 things that are closely related in AI interviews

* Candidate behavior that may not be allowed  
  * EF does not interpret the behavior, only flags it so that the human user can review and make a decision  
* Types of proctoring measures  
  * Objective list of action that get flagged  
  * This list will change over time, as EF learns more and evolves product

Example: v0 measures  
![][image31]

**Content patterns and related terms**

| Use | Guidelines and examples  | Do not use |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Flagged activity  | ![][image32]![][image33] ![][image34] | Flagged Activity |
| No flags  | 0 flagged activity  Communicates **low** need to review candidate behavior  | No Flags Unflagged |
| Warning | Some flagged activity  Exact range TBD Communicates **potential** need to review candidate behavior  | Warning\! |
| Critical | A lot of flagged activity  Exact range TBD Communicates **high** need to review candidate behavior  | Critical\! |

We use this term because:

* It describes the data: actions that were flagged by the system  
* It is neutral: we do not accuse candidates of cheating, we do not bias recruiters against candidates   
* It is scalable: specific enough to be clear, and broad enough to describe additional measures in the future  
  * For example, we may detect activity by an AI tool in the future. The term ‚Äúaction‚Äù suggests something a human does, while ‚Äúactivity‚Äù is broader.

* **Do not** use any ‚Äúmatch‚Äù terms unless your product or feature is actually leveraging this prediction model

Protect Eightfold competitive advantage by using this term correctly:

* Key differentiator \- inference and analysis of many types of data, it‚Äôs **not** just comparing skills in a resume to skills in a job description  
* Explainable AI \- makes the value of our AI easy to understand  
  * Solidity of Match Score: Valuable concept for Eightfold, and we must not dilute its meaning  
  * Match Score is the cornerstone of Eightfold‚Äôs explainable AI. It has been, and continues to be, thoroughly reviewed and tested, including for bias. Any other ‚Äúscoring‚Äù in connection needs to be distinguished from Eightfold match scoring.  
* Liability \- **do not** message that there is certainty in AI recommendations  
  * A score can give rise to automation bias and over-reliance

Definition

* Prediction of a candidate‚Äôs match to a particular opportunity  
  * Candidates are never scored   
    * Ex: we don‚Äôt score an individual‚Äôs value to a company or in the job market  
  * That means there is a different Match Score for each combination of person+job   
  * A person can have a strong Match Score for more than one job  
    * See ‚Äú[Match](#match-‚ö†Ô∏è)‚Äù for guidance about how to communicate specific scores  
* Calculated by Eightfold AI   
  * Uses global data set 1+ billion profiles and 1+ million skills  
  * Career information, like skills and the professional reputation of schools and companies  
  * Analysis, like adjacent skills and potential career paths  
  * Recalculated if an [AI interview score](#ai-interview-score) is added

Guidance

* Match Score  
  * Title case (capitalize both words)  
* Various scores  
  * Sentence case (do not always capitalize)  
  * Sometimes only visual   
  * See content patterns  
* There is no ‚Äúperfect match‚Äù or ‚Äúthe right match‚Äù  
  * **Do not** message certainty with AI recommendations  
  * Eightfold offers insights to empower the user: They decide what‚Äôs right for them

Content patterns

| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Match Score | Title case (capitalize each word) | Match score Match Star |

#### **Role** {#role}

* A capacity or function within a company.   
* Can also refer to a type of job a person is interested in pursuing. 

**Guidance**

* A role is a broader concept than ‚Äújob‚Äù or ‚Äúposition‚Äù.  
  * One person may fill multiple roles.  
* Use in product to communicate a wider range of responsibilities that are not limited to one specific position.   
* Generally, this term is used by HRBP and managers tasked with workforce planning because roles refer to the internal functioning of an organization and the distribution of responsibilities.

**Related terms**

* [Job](#job)  
* [Position](#position)  
* [Requisition](#requisition)

#### **Score ‚ö†Ô∏è**

Do **not** use ‚Äúscore‚Äù unless feature meets legal requirements 

* Legal requirements  
  * When ‚Äúscore‚Äù is used, product team must define the data and methodology used to calculate the score  
  * Scores must be tested for accuracy, validity, and bias  
* Risks  
  *   
  * A score can give rise to automation bias and over-reliance  
* Platform concerns  
  * Solidity of [Match Score](#match-score-‚ö†Ô∏è‚ö†Ô∏è‚ö†Ô∏è): Valuable concept for Eightfold, and we must not dilute its meaning  
    * Match Score is the cornerstone of Eightfold‚Äôs explainable AI. It has been, and continues to be, thoroughly reviewed and tested, including for bias. Any other ‚Äúscoring‚Äù in connection needs to be distinguished from Eightfold match scoring.  
  * Too many ‚Äúscores‚Äù will make our platform seem like a math book instead of a high quality product

**Definition**

* A numerical or systemic evaluation of performance, progress, or quality

**Alternative terms**

Avoid the compliance requirements and risks of ‚Äúscore‚Äù by using other terms

* (nothing)   
  * Maybe you don‚Äôt need a word  
* Analytics  
* Insights

**Case studies**

| Product | Concept | Not approved | Final content |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| TA | Help recruiters assess their progress on filling a position | Position score | Position health |
| TD | Help workforce planners assess the strength of their strategy | Future readiness score | Future readiness |

**Approved uses of ‚Äúscore‚Äù**

* [AI interview score](#ai-interview-score)  
* [Match Score](#match-score-‚ö†Ô∏è‚ö†Ô∏è‚ö†Ô∏è)

#### **Suggested, Suggestion** {#suggested,-suggestion}

Definition

* Show option for consideration

Guidance

* Use **Suggested** when offering general options to the user without the algorithmic backing or implied relevance of **Recommended**.   
* **Suggested** is different from **Recommended**  
  * Use **Recommended** when the platform is **intelligently guiding** the user towards options based on data and algorithms.  
  * Use **Suggested** when offering **options for consideration** based on common patterns or related by category.
